data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET Core+. It was removed because it corrupts application state by unwinding the stack at arbitrary points.
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also removed** — no longer needed since abort can't happen.
3. **`default(T)` for reference types** is still `null` but with nullable annotations enabled, the compiler will warn.

### Migrated Code

The modern pattern uses **`CancellationToken` + `Task.Run`**:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a cooperative cancellation timeout.
    /// The work delegate must observe the CancellationToken to stop promptly.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, just like the original Thread.Join(timeout) did.
            // If the task hasn't finished by the deadline, this throws.
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception aggregates to match original behavior.
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }

    // Overload preserving the original signature for non-cooperative callers.
    // ⚠️  The work cannot be forcibly stopped — it will run to completion
    //     in the background even after the timeout fires.
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        Task<T> task = Task.Run(work, CancellationToken.None);

        try
        {
            task.Wait(cts.Token);  // throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No forced termination** | Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, there is **no way** to kill a runaway delegate in .NET 8. The cooperative overload (`Func<CancellationToken, T>`) only works if `work` checks the token. |
| **Fire-and-forget leak** | The non-cooperative overload returns on timeout, but the `Task` keeps running on a thread-pool thread. If `work` holds locks or DB connections, those stay open. |
| **`Task.Wait` vs `.Result`** | Both throw `AggregateException`. Use `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` to get the original exception unwrapped. |
| **Thread-pool starvation** | The original code used a dedicated `Thread`. `Task.Run` uses the thread-pool. Long-blocking work can starve other tasks. For CPU-heavy/blocking work, consider `TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning`. |

### If You Truly Need Hard Termination

Run the work in a **separate process** — that's the only safe isolation boundary in .NET 8:

```csharp
// Last-resort sketch — out-of-process execution
var process = Process.Start("dotnet", "run --project WorkerApp");
if (!process.WaitForExit(timeout))
{
    process.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
    throw new TimeoutException("...");
}
```

### Async-First Alternative

If callers can be made `async`, prefer this over blocking:

```csharp
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
    Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    try
    {
        return await work(cts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

**Summary**: Replace `Thread.Abort` with cooperative `CancellationToken`. Prefer the `Func<CancellationToken, T>` overload so callees can actually stop. Use out-of-process isolation if you need hard kills.
